# Windows Packaged App Implementation Plan

Goal:

- Create a Windows packaged version of the Tauri app that users can run from an app icon with no Python, Node.js, Rust, npm, browser tab, command prompt, or manual setup.
- Start with a no-install portable package.
- Only add an installer if the portable package is not reliable enough for normal users.

Current assumptions:

- The Windows package must support both Windows 10 and Windows 11.
- The Windows package only needs to support 64-bit Intel/AMD machines.
- Windows on ARM is out of scope.
- The preferred delivery is a portable zip that users can unzip and run directly.
- A minimal installer is a fallback, not the first delivery target.
- End users will have administrator rights if needed.
- Users are allowed to run an unsigned downloaded app.
- The package will be shared by email if the file size allows it; if it is too large for email, it will be shared through a web-based download method.
- The package should not create a desktop shortcut.
- The app should keep logs/troubleshooting files in the same folder as the app.
- Uninstall or manual cleanup should remove app-owned logs/troubleshooting files.
- Generated workbooks are user files and should never be removed by uninstall or cleanup steps.
- Generated workbooks only need to be tested with local output folders, not shared/network drives.

Resolved decisions:

- Support Windows 10 and Windows 11.
- Build for 64-bit Intel/AMD Windows only.
- Do not plan for Windows on ARM.
- Code signing is not required for the first package.
- Users can run an unsigned downloaded app.
- Users will have administrator rights if needed.
- Portable zip delivery is acceptable.
- Do not create a desktop shortcut.
- Keep app logs/troubleshooting files beside the app.
- Remove app-owned logs/troubleshooting files during uninstall or manual cleanup.
- Test generated workbook output to local folders only.
- Distribution will be email first if the package size is reasonable, otherwise through a web download.

Implementation progress:

- Added `npm run desktop:package:windows` as the main Windows packaging command.
- Added `npm run desktop:package:windows:portable` to build the Windows sidecar, build the Tauri app without an installer bundle, and create a portable zip.
- Added `npm run desktop:package:windows:installer` as the installer fallback command.
- Added `scripts/package-windows-portable.mjs` to assemble `Pella Order Automation Windows Portable.zip` from the Windows release executable and generator sidecar.
- Added Windows-only generation logging to `pella-order-automation.log` beside the app executable.
- Added `.github/workflows/windows-package.yml` to build the Windows portable zip on a hosted GitHub Actions Windows runner.

Packaging commands:

- Preferred portable package: `npm run desktop:package:windows`
- Explicit portable package: `npm run desktop:package:windows:portable`
- Installer fallback: `npm run desktop:package:windows:installer`

GitHub Actions build path:

- Workflow name: `Build Windows Portable Package`
- Manual trigger: GitHub repository -> Actions -> Build Windows Portable Package -> Run workflow.
- The workflow uses a hosted `windows-latest` runner, installs Node.js, Python, Rust, npm dependencies, and Python generator dependencies, then runs `npm run desktop:package:windows`.
- The output artifact is named `Pella Order Automation Windows Portable`.
- The artifact contains `Pella Order Automation Windows Portable.zip`.

Open questions to resolve before implementation:

1. Is Microsoft Edge WebView2 already installed on target machines?
   - Current answer: unknown.
   - Plan response: explicitly test on a clean Windows 10 and Windows 11 machine, and decide whether a WebView2 bootstrapper or installer path is needed if the portable app does not launch.

Step-by-step plan:

1. Confirm the target Windows environment.
   - Build for Windows 10 and Windows 11.
   - Build for 64-bit Intel/AMD Windows only.
   - Do not support Windows on ARM for this package.
   - Treat unsigned-app execution as acceptable for the first release.
   - Keep code signing as a future option only if SmartScreen or company policy becomes a blocker.

2. Prepare a Windows build machine.
   - Prefer the hosted GitHub Actions Windows runner in `.github/workflows/windows-package.yml`.
   - Use a real Windows machine or Windows VM only if GitHub Actions is unavailable.
   - Install Node.js/npm.
   - Install Rust/Cargo with the MSVC toolchain.
   - Install Python 3.11+.
   - Install Python dependencies, including `openpyxl` and `PyInstaller`.
   - Confirm `npm`, `cargo`, `rustc`, and `python` are available from PowerShell.

3. Check out or copy the project onto the Windows build machine.
   - Use the same project files that successfully produced the macOS DMG.
   - Do not require end users to receive these project files.
   - Keep build-only tooling on the build machine, not inside the final user package unless Tauri bundles it intentionally.

4. Verify the app still works in Windows development mode.
   - Run the frontend build with `npm run build`.
   - Run the Tauri development app with `npm run desktop:dev`.
   - Confirm the app opens normally.
   - Confirm native file pickers work.
   - Confirm paths with spaces work.

5. Run Windows smoke tests for the generator.
   - Generate output from Example 1.
   - Generate output from Example 2.
   - Confirm output workbooks are created.
   - Confirm warnings/errors appear as expected.
   - Fix any Windows-specific path or file-locking issues before packaging.

6. Build the Windows generator sidecar.
   - Run `npm run sidecar:build` on Windows.
   - Confirm a Windows executable is created under `src-tauri/binaries/`.
   - Expected filename pattern: `pella-generator-x86_64-pc-windows-msvc.exe`.
   - Confirm the sidecar runs without a local Python install dependency.

7. Build the Windows Tauri package.
   - Preferred path: run the `Build Windows Portable Package` GitHub Actions workflow.
   - Local/VM path: run `npm run desktop:package:windows:portable` on Windows.
   - Inspect the generated executable under `src-tauri/target/release/`.
   - Confirm the portable package includes both `Pella Order Automation.exe` and `pella-generator.exe`.
   - The portable script should also create `dist/Pella Order Automation Windows Portable.zip`.

8. Create the first portable package.
   - Use `scripts/package-windows-portable.mjs` to create a clean app folder under `dist/windows-portable/Pella Order Automation`.
   - Zip that folder as `dist/Pella Order Automation Windows Portable.zip`.
   - The intended user flow is:
     1. Unzip the folder.
     2. Open `Pella Order Automation.exe`.
     3. Generate the workbook.
   - No installer should be required for this first attempt.
   - Do not include or create a desktop shortcut.
   - Keep logs/troubleshooting files inside the unzipped app folder as `pella-order-automation.log`.

9. Test the portable package on a clean Windows machine.
   - Use a machine or VM that does not have Python, Node.js, Rust, npm, or the project repo installed.
   - Unzip the portable package.
   - Launch the app by double-clicking the `.exe`.
   - Generate Example 1 output.
   - Generate Example 2 output.
   - Save generated outputs to local folders only.
   - Confirm no command prompt or manual dependency installation is required.
   - Test on both Windows 10 and Windows 11.
   - Record whether Microsoft Edge WebView2 is present and whether the app launches without extra WebView2 setup.

10. Record any portable-app friction.
    - Note any SmartScreen warning.
    - Note any antivirus/Windows Defender warning.
    - Note any missing WebView/runtime issue.
    - Note whether users need to right-click/open, unblock the zip, or approve anything unexpected.
    - If friction is minor, keep the portable package as the preferred delivery.

11. Add an installer only if needed.
    - Run `npm run desktop:package:windows:installer`.
    - Use the standard Tauri Windows NSIS installer output.
    - Users have administrator rights, but prefer the cleanest install path that allows app-folder logs without requiring the app itself to run elevated.
    - Install only the app files, bundled sidecar, app icon, optional Start Menu entry, and uninstaller.
    - Do not create a desktop shortcut.
    - Avoid background services, startup tasks, shell extensions, global PATH changes, registry-heavy configuration, and external dependency installers.
    - If WebView2 is missing on target machines, decide whether to use an installer path that handles WebView2 cleanly.

12. Test installer behavior if the installer path is used.
    - Install on a clean Windows machine.
    - Confirm the app appears in Windows Settings under installed apps.
    - Launch from the installed app location or Start Menu if a Start Menu entry is created.
    - Generate Example 1 and Example 2 outputs.
    - Save generated outputs to local folders only.
    - Confirm logs/troubleshooting files are written in the app folder.
    - Uninstall from Windows Settings.
    - Confirm the app install directory, bundled sidecar, app-owned logs/troubleshooting files, shortcuts if any, and installer registration are removed.
    - Confirm user-created output workbooks are not deleted.

13. Decide whether code signing is needed.
    - Code signing is not required for the first package because users can run an unsigned app.
    - If SmartScreen or company security policy later blocks normal use, investigate code signing.
    - Record the signing decision before handing the package to non-technical users.

14. Document the final Windows user flow.
    - For portable delivery, document only unzip, open app, select files, generate workbook.
    - For installer delivery, document only run installer, open app, select files, generate workbook, uninstall from Windows Settings.
    - Do not include developer setup steps in end-user instructions.
    - For manual portable cleanup, document that deleting the unzipped app folder removes the app and its logs/troubleshooting files.

15. Final acceptance check.
    - A non-technical user can open the app from an icon.
    - The app works without Python, Node.js, npm, Rust, or repo files.
    - The packaged app uses the bundled generator sidecar.
    - The app can select PO/work-order files and save the completed workbook to a user-selected location.
    - Portable delivery leaves no installed system components behind.
    - Portable cleanup removes app-owned logs/troubleshooting files by deleting the app folder.
    - Installer delivery, if used, uninstalls cleanly.
    - User-created workbook outputs are preserved.
    - Example 1 and Example 2 work from the packaged Windows app.
    - The package is verified on both Windows 10 and Windows 11.
